data.name: richTextBox2.Text
data.value: You can backup any of your drives (NTFS/FAT32/REDFS) in any order. An optimized algorithm determines what data is already present on the backup server and transmits only the modified data, with as low network utilization as possible. This is achieved by tracking file system divergence from common parent drives and with special block modification tracking algorithm. You can still enable deduplication and compression on the backup destination even if these features are disabled in the local filesystems. i.e Asymetric configuration is supported.

data.name: richTextBox1.Text
data.value: Using this feature, you can create 'raw' drives that appears to windows explorer as real physical disks. These can be formatted as either NTFS/FAT32. Additionally, you can also take snapshots and clones of these drives exactly like RedFS drives! :-). Ultimately this means that you can get features such as clones/snapshots/deduplication/compression for you NTFS/FAT32 Virtual drives, and full cross filesystem deduplication (yes!) for NTFS/FAT32/REDFS. (You need the Redfs_initiator to mount these drives in windows)

data.name: richTextBox3.Text
data.value: Backup your local disk contents into RedFS. This feature allows you to do only incremental backups, i.e Only files that have changed since the last backup are copied into Redfs. Entire files are not usually copied, only the deltas are -at 4kb chunksizes. This technique is superefficient for large VMs, Outlook files etc. Moverover you can use this as a versioning system of your backups overtime.
